      "type": "teach",
      "title": "Building longer words",
      "body": "Once you know your consonants and short vowels, you can sound out almost any short word — even ones with a few letters bunched together. Take 𐑛𐑧𐑕𐑒: 𐑛 (d) 𐑧 (e) 𐑕 (s) 𐑒 (k) blends into \"desk\". Sound it out slowly, then speed up."
    },
    {
      "type": "type",
      "prompt": "𐑜𐑦𐑓𐑑",
      "caption": "Type what this word says",
      "correct": "gift",
      "correctLabel": "gift"
    },
    {
      "type": "teach",
      "title": "Consonant clusters",
      "body": "Some words stack two or three consonants right next to each other, like desk (d-e-s-k) or test (t-e-s-t). Just sound out each letter in order — Shavian never skips a beat, even when English spelling would."
